WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.414
Okay.

00:03.595 --> 00:04.536
So how do they do it?

00:05.317 --> 00:11.324
Via what they call trajectory, via regularization of trajectory optimization.

00:11.924 --> 00:14.527
So in essence, what do we want to regularize here?

00:14.768 --> 00:25.920
There are many things we could do to solve this, but the way this paper goes is they say we not only do we want the most return, we also

00:25.900 --> 00:32.914
want a high log probability of our taken path.

00:33.375 --> 00:39.446
So this here, as you can see, this is observation action and so on, observation action.

00:39.767 --> 00:41.310
So this is the future.

00:41.691 --> 00:44.837
This right here is the future.

00:46.994 --> 00:55.210
So this, this sequence here is going, is what is going to give me the reward right here.

00:55.550 --> 00:56.131
Right.

00:56.152 --> 01:00.881
So G is also dependent on these things, but it's not said explicitly here.

01:00.961 --> 01:04.788
So G is dependent on your plan or maybe let's not call this the future.

01:04.828 --> 01:05.830
This is the plan.

01:07.058 --> 01:07.439
Okay.

01:07.719 --> 01:09.101
This is the plan you came up with.

01:10.122 --> 01:14.508
So this is directly going to influence G and G is the reward you're going to get under your model.

01:14.828 --> 01:19.314
But also you want the log probability of the plan itself to be high.

01:20.216 --> 01:28.246
Now there, I think there is a bit, there is something missing here and that is conditioned on your training distribution right here.

01:28.847 --> 01:31.451
And I think that's a actually a rather crucial part.

01:32.092 --> 01:34.635
No, that's, that's the KL thing.

01:34.615 --> 01:36.478
So this is conditioned on your training.

01:36.738 --> 01:44.972
So what you want is you want the plan to be basically in your training distribution.

01:45.533 --> 01:56.050
So you want your plan that you're going to execute if that is actually part of your training data set.

01:56.030 --> 02:10.071
then you know I have already executed this once before and it's reasonable to assume that therefore my world model has learned from this experience and is going to give me an accurate reward.

02:10.611 --> 02:14.477
If we go back to our rooms example then

02:14.457 --> 02:16.762
up here somewhere.

02:17.183 --> 02:26.161
If we go back to our room's example, you see that anywhere in the green area where I have already explored, the world model is fairly good.

02:26.462 --> 02:33.597
It's going to give me accurate reflection of the world, but as soon as I go outside the green area, it is not.

02:33.577 --> 02:38.805
And inside the green area is basically where my training data is.

02:39.286 --> 02:45.735
Now, if I in the future actually take a path here, crash into a wall right here, right?

02:45.915 --> 02:52.666
You saw in the algorithm, at the end of an episode, I'm going to add my trajectory to the training data for the world model.

02:52.686 --> 02:56.351
So this green part here expands to include that.

02:56.852 --> 03:00.377
And now, if I go here again,

03:00.357 --> 03:07.585
If my plan goes there again, now I can trust the world model, but also now it has, it is actually correct because it has a wall here.

03:08.105 --> 03:24.062
So you see that the regularization basically, not only do I want the biggest reward possible under my world model, I also want that the plan that I'm about to execute is, has a high probability under my training distribution.

03:24.582 --> 03:24.862
Okay.

03:25.463 --> 03:29.267
And the way we do this is by denoising auto-encoders.

03:31.424 --> 03:40.050
So I want the log probability here to be high and you do this via a denoising autoencoder.

